s=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>L</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L_i</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3117em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>","key":"MtqavGmEje"},{"type":"text","value":" (for ","position":{"start":{"line":90,"column":1},"end":{"line":90,"column":1}},"key":"BAxfdzDzf2"},{"type":"inlineMath","value":"i^{th}","position":{"start":{"line":90,"column":1},"end":{"line":90,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>i</mi><mrow><mi>t</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">i^{th}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">t</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">h</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>","key":"HwWAEGRlu0"},{"type":"text","value":" data point) will be calculated. The total loss is the sum of losses of all the individual data points. We minimize the average of the total loss and the not the total loss. Minimizing the average loss implies that the total loss is getting minimized.","position":{"start":{"line":90,"column":1},"end":{"line":90,"column":1}},"key":"gOdljKOcoO"}],"key":"IgcuK3sgaO"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":92,"column":1},"end":{"line":92,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"For a large neural network, the number of weight elements and biases becomes so large and minimizing the loss with so many parameters is a difficult task. This complex task is achieved using gradient descent.","position":{"start":{"line":92,"column":1},"end":{"line":92,"column":1}},"key":"iC5Lo3ekid"}],"key":"MIOvjYCK5q"},{"type":"container","kind":"figure","children":[{"type":"image","url":"/build/image4-790f22d98ef914b45fb0c0a6dc362932.gif","alt":"📖Source","data":{"altTextIsAutoGenerated":true},"key":"WjbUlK5SBo","urlSource":"images/image4.gif"},{"type":"caption","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"captionNumber","kind":"figure","label":"image4","identifier":"image4","html_id":"image4","enumerator":"3","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Figure ","key":"A3ZwqxwXXL"},{"type":"text","value":"3","key":"MfiKpu3aJD"},{"type":"text","value":":","key":"R3tjj3rJbS"}],"template":"Figure %s:","key":"OdKxlyt761"},{"type":"link","url":"https://machinelearningknowledge.ai/animated-explanation-of-feed-forward-neural-network-architecture/","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"📖Source","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"key":"A7a7PoF1na"}],"urlSource":"https://machinelearningknowledge.ai/animated-explanation-of-feed-forward-neural-network-architecture/","key":"ICnalEtvSn"}],"key":"wfp4vKWc2B"}],"key":"qvn0o3pkpd"}],"label":"image4","identifier":"image4","enumerator":"4","html_id":"image4","key":"xIOzKSYODN"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":102,"column":1},"end":{"line":102,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"For updating weights and biases using plain backpropagation, you have to scan through the entire data set to make a single update to the weights. This is computationally very expensive for large datasets. Thus, you use multiple batches (or ","position":{"start":{"line":102,"column":1},"end":{"line":102,"column":1}},"key":"WNgD0bXQW2"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":102,"column":1},"end":{"line":102,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"mini-batches","position":{"start":{"line":102,"column":1},"end":{"line":102,"column":1}},"key":"V23kLjUQSz"}],"key":"BxV63TYHym"},{"type":"text","value":") of data points, compute the average gradient for a batch, and update the weights based on that gradient.","position":{"start":{"line":102,"column":1},"end":{"line":102,"column":1}},"key":"Wfbu2wW36R"}],"key":"we9Vrf1sYz"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":104,"column":1},"end":{"line":104,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"But there is a danger in doing this - you are making weight updates based only on gradients computed for small batches, not the entire training set. Thus, you make multiple passes through the entire training set using epochs. An epoch is one pass through the entire training set, and you use multiple epochs (typically 10, 20, 50, 100 etc.) while training. In each epoch, you reshuffle all the data points, divide the reshuffled set into m batches, and update weights based on gradient of each batch.","position":{"start":{"line":104,"column":1},"end":{"line":104,"column":1}},"key":"Ru8s2LKLVP"}],"key":"MVYpJF1lDa"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":106,"column":1},"end":{"line":106,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD)","position":{"start":{"line":106,"column":1},"end":{"line":106,"column":1}},"key":"YWDkWoVQwT"}],"identifier":"stochastic-gradient-descent-sgd","label":"Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD)","html_id":"stochastic-gradient-descent-sgd","implicit":true,"key":"wAYTIxop3R"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":108,"column":1},"end":{"line":108,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In most libraries such as Tensorflow, the SGD training procedure is as follows:","position":{"start":{"line":108,"column":1},"end":{"line":108,"column":1}},"key":"UVHGhs90py"}],"key":"fP3x4LGZul"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":109,"column":1},"end":{"line":114,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":109,"column":1},"end":{"line":109,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"You specify the number of epochs (typical values are 10, 20, 50, 100 etc.) - more epochs require more computational power","position":{"start":{"line":109,"column":1},"end":{"line":109,"column":1}},"key":"VQylQKNPfh"}],"key":"OlIvb258AM"}],"key":"nYoRr0mCwh"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":110,"column":1},"end":{"line":110,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"You specify the number of batches ","position":{"start":{"line":110,"column":1},"end":{"line":110,"column":1}},"key":"V8SviWlMwb"},{"type":"inlineMath","value":"m","position":{"start":{"line":110,"column":1},"end":{"line":110,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">m</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span></span></span></span>","key":"Gv5fEXavTW"},{"type":"text","value":" (typical values are 32, 64, 128, etc.)","position":{"start":{"line":110,"column":1},"end":{"line":110,"column":1}},"key":"xJjpJeqpBl"}],"key":"tFUDalXOG3"}],"key":"cAm6C0wr17"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"At the start of each epoch, the data set is reshuffled and divided into ","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"key":"LUiIkencGO"},{"type":"inlineMath","value":"m","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">m</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span></span></span></span>","key":"mcNGFaurAk"},{"type":"text","value":" batches","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"key":"JD8iWPrBeG"}],"key":"Y84f8TSJkP"}],"key":"hDZum9RzpO"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":112,"column":1},"end":{"line":112,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"The average gradient of each batch is then used to make a weight update","position":{"start":{"line":112,"column":1},"end":{"line":112,"column":1}},"key":"E1Vn1hfU1y"}],"key":"gT9rsTDDmS"}],"key":"F1ztITx0Ki"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":113,"column":1},"end":{"line":114,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"The training is complete at the end of all the epochs","position":{"start":{"line":113,"column":1},"end":{"line":113,"column":1}},"key":"AzgJmR2rUx"}],"key":"odKkVtrC0d"}],"key":"Fl9y3L8jzf"}],"key":"rcI9wjAyVI"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":115,"column":1},"end":{"line":116,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Apart from being computationally faster, the SGD training process has another big advantage - it actually helps you reach the global minima (instead of being stuck at a local minima). Also, to avoid the problem of getting stuck at a local optimum, you need to strike a balance between exploration and exploitation.\nExploration means that you try to minimize the loss function with different starting points of ","position":{"start":{"line":115,"column":1},"end":{"line":115,"column":1}},"key":"U6E8bY99j8"},{"type":"inlineMath","value":"W","position":{"start":{"line":115,"column":1},"end":{"line":115,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>W</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">W</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">W</span></span></span></span>","key":"K3IJsXl4Dy"},{"type":"text","value":" and ","position":{"start":{"line":115,"column":1},"end":{"line":115,"column":1}},"key":"qrmzLPbBKE"},{"type":"inlineMath","value":"b","position":{"start":{"line":115,"column":1},"end":{"line":115,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">b</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span></span></span></span>","key":"XPCh6kW1JT"},{"type":"text","value":", i.e., you initialize ","position":{"start":{"line":115,"column":1},"end":{"line":115,"column":1}},"key":"RQgWW6sJoZ"},{"type":"inlineMath","value":"W","position":{"start":{"line":115,"column":1},"end":{"line":115,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>W</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">W</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">W</span></span></span></span>","key":"qUTM1muQL0"},{"type":"text","value":" and ","position":{"start":{"line":115,"column":1},"end":{"line":115,"column":1}},"key":"W7QWefa30D"},{"type":"inlineMath","value":"b","position":{"start":{"line":115,"column":1},"end":{"line":115,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">b</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span></span></span></span>","key":"n1gn14OutM"},{"type":"text","value":" with different values. On the other hand, exploitation means that you try to reach the global minima starting from a particular W and b and do not explore the terrain at all. That might lead you to the lowest point locally, but not the necessarily the global minimum.","position":{"start":{"line":115,"column":1},"end":{"line":115,"column":1}},"key":"kzRa0a43q7"}],"key":"oZjYjjLQhC"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":118,"column":1},"end":{"line":118,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Modifications in Neural Networks","position":{"start":{"line":118,"column":1},"end":{"line":118,"column":1}},"key":"u6FZolm3aS"}],"identifier":"modifications-in-neural-networks","label":"Modifications in Neural Networks","html_id":"modifications-in-neural-networks","implicit":true,"key":"wDLFoa79pL"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":120,"column":1},"end":{"line":120,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Neural networks are usually large, complex models with tens of thousands of parameters, and thus tend to overfit the training data. As with many other ML models, regularization is a common technique used in neural networks to address this problem.","position":{"start":{"line":120,"column":1},"end":{"line":120,"column":1}},"key":"GwVIm1eds3"}],"key":"m5L9JYX1Dm"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":122,"column":1},"end":{"line":123,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The ‘parameter norm’ regularization is similar to that in linear regression in almost every aspect. As in lasso regression (L1 norm), we get a sparse weight matrix, which is not the case with the L2 norm. Despite this fact, the L2 norm is more common because the sum of the squares term is easily differentiable which comes in handy during backpropagation.\nApart from using the parameter norm, there is another popular neural network regularization technique called ","position":{"start":{"line":122,"column":1},"end":{"line":122,"column":1}},"key":"gFfjJmUBVV"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":122,"column":1},"end":{"line":122,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"dropouts","position":{"start":{"line":122,"column":1},"end":{"line":122,"column":1}},"key":"YYOKAv9HyO"}],"key":"t3iS4MxmRw"},{"type":"text","value":".","position":{"start":{"line":122,"column":1},"end":{"line":122,"column":1}},"key":"NYaSyq8FWw"}],"key":"rtZ82Bel0i"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":125,"column":1},"end":{"line":125,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Dropouts","position":{"start":{"line":125,"column":1},"end":{"line":125,"column":1}},"key":"pvBnyqSAas"}],"identifier":"dropouts","label":"Dropouts","html_id":"dropouts","implicit":true,"key":"Yr9wb43Lny"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":127,"column":1},"end":{"line":127,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Some important points to note regarding dropouts are:","position":{"start":{"line":127,"column":1},"end":{"line":127,"column":1}},"key":"pZ9ht5NtAd"}],"key":"McOGJGsOlq"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":128,"column":1},"end":{"line":131,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":128,"column":1},"end":{"line":128,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Dropouts can be applied only to some layers of the network (in fact, that is a common practice - you choose some layer arbitrarily to apply dropouts to)","position":{"start":{"line":128,"column":1},"end":{"line":128,"column":1}},"key":"NoAojA91ba"}],"key":"gTGc9ZWT66"}],"key":"BB84IkrDqF"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":129,"column":1},"end":{"line":129,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"The mask ","position":{"start":{"line":129,"column":1},"end":{"line":129,"column":1}},"key":"GScDEQRkUK"},{"type":"inlineMath","value":"\\alpha","position":{"start":{"line":129,"column":1},"end":{"line":129,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span>","key":"wE653Q7aTj"},{"type":"text","value":" is generated independently for each layer during feedforward, and the same mask is used in backpropagation","position":{"start":{"line":129,"column":1},"end":{"line":129,"column":1}},"key":"iwhwlKgDxF"}],"key":"tg7gel2IvK"}],"key":"NMxqxkQCTh"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":130,"column":1},"end":{"line":131,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"The mask changes with each minibatch/iteration, are randomly generated in each iteration (sampled from a Bernoulli with some ","position":{"start":{"line":130,"column":1},"end":{"line":130,"column":1}},"key":"g3SSaVQbxM"},{"type":"inlineMath","value":"p(1)=q","position":{"start":{"line":130,"column":1},"end":{"line":130,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p(1)=q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">q</span></span></span></span>","key":"Mrcae6TWoH"},{"type":"text","value":")","position":{"start":{"line":130,"column":1},"end":{"line":130,"column":1}},"key":"EI31XZdQCu"}],"key":"G4X6DM8Pt2"}],"key":"MKl3qhG0JY"}],"key":"WKk6xM7xeL"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":132,"column":1},"end":{"line":132,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Why the dropout strategy works well is explained through the notion of a manifold. Manifold captures the observation that in high dimensional spaces, the data points often actually lie in a lower-dimensional manifold. The dropout strategy uses this fact to find a lower-dimensional solution to the problem.","position":{"start":{"line":132,"column":1},"end":{"line":132,"column":1}},"key":"kilpXMtPrs"}],"key":"wmN0H2D2iN"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":134,"column":1},"end":{"line":134,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Dropouts help in symmetry breaking as well. There is every possibility of the creation of communities within neurons which restricts them from learning independently. Hence, by setting some random set of the weights to zero in every iteration, this community/symmetry is broken. Note that there, a different mini batch is processed in every iteration in an epoch, and dropouts are applied to each mini batch.","position":{"start":{"line":134,"column":1},"end":{"line":134,"column":1}},"key":"OZaZhzSl4Y"}],"key":"qpuzeSrtRL"}],"key":"WGhQsir2Mi"}],"key":"NLbAH3RqXK"},"references":{"cite":{"order":[],"data":{}}},"footer":{"navigation":{"prev":{"title":"Anomaly Detection","url":"/anomaly-detection","group":"Algorithms"},"next":{"title":"Recurrent Neural Network","url":"/recurrent-neural-network","group":"Neural Network"}}},"domain":"http://localhost:3000"}